not be rectified; true honesty + courage + integrity require that he take this implacable stand of con‐ fronting the is qua is. To start supposing transmundane intervention undoes the very basis of moral value built into his realization; that it is a hopeless situation + that he faces This absolutely. Thus to him \"Valis\" is more dangerous than it is to a more ignorant person who is able to deny or ignore the problems raised as insane, morbid or self-indulgent. \"Valis\" is dangerous because upon stating the problem in a modern way - it thereupon draws on a solution so absurd + obsolete that it - the solution - seems to insult the integrity of the very person able to perceive the reality of the problem! \"Valis,\" then, aims at the most modern + sophisticated reader + then presents him with a \"solution\" as foolish as the problems stated are real what he does not see is that \"Valis\" is written backward, from solution (soteriology) to problem (verfallheit). The author is stipulating the problem only to account for the existence of the solution (he has reasoned back from the soteriological experience to the problem): he knows the solution firsthand + infers the problem sing it as his premise. \"Valis\" then, only eems to be an existential work; in reality it a Gnostic Gospel, + its main concern is with the perpetual transmundane savior who ome's here (again + agains under a variety of vames. For example, Fat is (when you look losely) stated to be mad because he later on ceases to be m, of C-187 restoration is homologized with his anticipation of the imminent birth of the new savior (more accurately newest incarnation of the one perpetual savior). \"Valis\" falls, then into these sections: Fat ill; transmundane intervention; his recovery due to it; his search - in his condition of repair - for the new incarnation of the perpetual savior. For \"Valis\" to make sense, as Galbreath be points out the transmundane deity must presumed, + the book does not quite do this; 